<p>I came across this in some very old VB code:</p>  <pre><code>If (Ans.FormatFlags And StringFormatFlags.NoClip) &lt;&gt; 0 Then     FF = FF And Not StringFormatFlags.NoClip </code></pre>  <p>I'm not 100% sure what this is trying to do, but I think it's seeing if the flag "is not set" in FF?</p>  <p>If so, what is the equivalent C#...</p>  <pre><code>!StringFormatFlags.NoClip </code></pre>  <p>doesn't work because you can't apply ! to a StringFormatFlags.</p>  <pre><code>!(int)StringFormatFlags.NoClip </code></pre>  <p>doesn't work because you can't apply ! to a int.</p>  <p>Do I use != 0 here or is there a simpler in-line method?</p>